<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName authority="Mulsant, 1850" authorityName="Mulsant" authorityYear="1850" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Aspidimerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aspidimerus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<pageBreakToken pageId="2" pageNumber="49" start="start">Aspidimerus</pageBreakToken>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Cryptogonus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cryptogonus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cryptogonus</taxonomicName>
Mulsant. However, it can be easily distinguished from the latter as follows: prosternum T-shaped, evenly convex (Fig. 2), prosternal lines as wide apart as the base of prosternal process; the area between them extremely convex and widening anteriorly to form a chin-band, usually with coarse punctures and long pubescence (Fig. 5); body moderately large (length 2.8-5.0 mm); oblong oval, moderately convex; pronotum with the posterior angles pointed and lateral margin straight (Fig. 1). The prosternal lines of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Cryptogonus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cryptogonus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cryptogonus</taxonomicName>
are not as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Mulsant, 1850" authorityName="Mulsant" authorityYear="1850" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Aspidimerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aspidimerus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Aspidimerus</taxonomicName>
, varying in outline, the area enclosed by them lying at the same level as the rest of prosternum; body small, rounded oval.
</paragraph>
